arkdown-content">
<p>Ever stood in a long line and thought to yourself, "There has to be a be=
tter way to do this"? That's where queuing theory enters the picture.&nbsp;=
</p> <p>Essentially, queuing theory is the study of line formation, how the=
y flow, and how we can improve them. Don't worry, though=E2=80=94this isn't=
 something mathematicians find in the lab. It's something that affects dail=
y life, from waiting at the DMV to getting a coffee.&nbsp;</p> <p>Understan=
ding how queues work can help companies get people in and out more quickly,=
 reduce frustration, and increase overall satisfaction.&nbsp;</p> <p>In thi=
s beginner's guide, we'll take a look at the basics of how queuing works, d=
efine important terms in simple terms, and show you how this theory is used=
 in real life.</p> <h2 id=3D"b-what-is-queuing-theory-b" class=3D"scroll-an=
chor"><b>What Is Queuing Theory?</b></h2> <p><a href=3D"https://www.qminder=
.com/blog/queue-management/queuing-theory-customer-service/" rel=3D"externa=
l nofollow noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank"><b>Queuing theory</b></a>=
 is all about studying how individuals wait, why individuals wait, and how =
systems make individuals wait=E2=80=94be that the hospital triage queue, th=
e drive-thru at a fast food place, or customer service on a Monday morning.=
</p> <p>The entire process started with a Danish engineer, <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agner_Krarup_Erlang" rel=3D"external nofollow noop=
ener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank" data-cmp-ab=3D"2"><b>Agner Krarup Erlang=
</b></a>, in the early <b>1900s</b>. He was working for the Copenhagen Tele=
phone Company and needed to determine how many lines of phone you have to e=
nsure that people do not wait forever.&nbsp;</p> <p>His work was so powerfu=
l that phone traffic is now measured in "<b>erlangs</b>"=E2=80=93a unit tha=
t bears his name.</p> <h3 id=3D"b-why-it-is-still-relevant-today-b" class=
=3D"scroll-anchor"><b>Why It Is Still Relevant Today</b></h3> <p>If you thi=
nk queuing theory doesn't belong in an out-of-date textbook, think again. T=
he queuing process comes up more frequently than you'd guess: DMVs, airport=
s, clinics, call centers, retail store checkouts, even coffee shops at 8 a.=
m. on Monday.</p> <p>And the thing is, how we handle those lines really doe=
s impact customer experience. A well-handled line makes people feel taken c=
are of and keeps things moving.&nbsp;</p> <p>A badly handled one? Frustrati=
on in an instant.</p> <p>Learning about the fundamentals of queuing theory =
presents companies with the opportunity to better organize=E2=80=94assignin=
g personnel, re-scheduling timetables, or even reconfiguring service arrang=
ements.&nbsp;</p> <p>That is why uses of queuing theory are so beneficial: =
it minimizes waiting, maximizes teams, and simplifies the entire process fo=
r all involved.</p> <h2 id=3D"b-understanding-the-queuing-process-b" class=
=3D"scroll-anchor"><b>Understanding the Queuing Process</b></h2> <p>Before =
we look at some applications of queuing theory, let's have a sense of why a=
 queue is there in the first place. Whether you're working with lines at a =
store, hospital, or call center, the dynamics just so happen to be eerily t=
he same.</p> <h3 id=3D"b-major-elements-of-a-queue-b" class=3D"scroll-ancho=
r"><b>Major Elements of a Queue</b></h3> <p>All queues, simple or sophistic=
ated, share four broad elements. Consider these the wheels that turn behind=
 the scenes:</p> <ul> <li><p><b>Arrival: </b>This is when and how people ar=
rive in the queue. Are they arriving at random? Checking in online? <a href=
=3D"https://www.qminder.com/solutions/appointment-scheduling-software/" rel=
=3D"external nofollow noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank"><b>Scheduling =
appointments</b></a>? Arrival behavior is the foundation of traffic predict=
ion. Traffic forecasting depends on this.</p></li> <li><p><b>Capacity:</b> =
Some systems can serve an infinite number of waiting individuals (think of =
an online chat line), while others, such as a waiting area in a small clini=
c, cannot. Understanding your capacity prevents bottlenecks.</p></li> <li><=
p><b>Service: </b>Where and how customers are served. It is a customer in a=
 store, a triage nurse in an emergency room, or a support representative on=
 the telephone. Speed and availability of service tend to make or break cus=
tomer queue experience.</p></li> <li><p><b>Departure:</b> When service is c=
ompleted, the customer leaves the system. But how quickly that happens=E2=
=80=94and whether or not they're satisfied with it=E2=80=94will tell you a =
lot about your overall queuing process.</p></li> </ul> <p>Awareness of thes=
e elements isn't abstract=E2=80=94It's practical. The more efficiently your=
 queue serves, the more pleasant the experience for everyone involved.</p> =
<h2 id=3D"b-common-queue-models-b" class=3D"scroll-anchor"><b>Common Queue =
Models</b></h2> <p>Now a bit of theory=E2=80=94but don=E2=80=99t worry, we=
=E2=80=99ll keep it grounded and practical.</p> <h3 id=3D"a-href-https-en-w=
ikipedia-org-wiki-little-27s-law-b-little-39-s-law-b-a" class=3D"scroll-anc=
hor"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Little%27s_law" rel=3D"extern=
al nofollow noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank" data-cmp-ab=3D"2"><b>Lit=
tle's Law</b></a></h3> <p>John Little came up with a simple but powerful eq=
uation. It connects three things in a queue: how many people are in the sys=
tem (L), how often they arrive (=CE=BB), and how long they stay (W). The fo=
rmula is:</p> <p><b>L =3D =CE=BBW</b></p> <p>Let=E2=80=99s say you run a re=
staurant. If 10 people arrive every hour and each stays for 1 hour, that me=
ans there are 10 people in the system at any given time.<br> <b>L =3D 10 =
=C3=97 1 =3D 10</b></p> <p>This is useful when you=E2=80=99re trying to fig=
ure out staffing, seating, or even kitchen flow.</p> <p>Now, if more people=
 arrive or they take longer to leave, your system fills up.</p> <p>For exam=
ple:</p> <ul> <li><p>If arrival rate doubles and service time stays the sam=
e, your queue doubles.</p></li> <li><p>If service time doubles while arriva=
ls stay steady, again=E2=80=94your queue doubles.</p></li> </ul> <p>You don=
=E2=80=99t need to memorize this, but understanding how these pieces fit to=
gether can help you avoid long waits and crowded lobbies.</p> <h3 id=3D"b-k=
endall-s-notation-b" class=3D"scroll-anchor"><b>Kendall=E2=80=99s Notation<=
/b></h3> <p>This is a way to describe different types of queuing systems. D=
avid George Kendall introduced it, and it uses a simple format:</p> <p><b>A=
/S/c/K/N/D</b>, where:</p> <ul> <li><p><b>A </b>for the arrival process.</p=
></li> <li><p><b>S </b>for the mathematical distribution of the service tim=
e.</p></li> <li><p><b>c </b>for the number of servers.</p></li> <li><p><b>K=
 </b>for the capacity of the queue (if not unlimited).</p></li> <li><p><b>N=
</b> for the number of possible customers (if not infinite).</p></li> <li><=
p><b>D </b>for the queuing discipline (first-in, first-out by default).</p>=
</li> </ul> <p>In most real-world cases, you only need the first three: <b>=
A/S/c</b>.</p> <p>A common example is <b>M/M/1</b>, which means:</p> <ul> <=
li><p>Random (Markovian) arrivals</p></li> <li><p>Random service times</p><=
/li> <li><p>One server</p></li> </ul> <p>You=E2=80=99ll also see models lik=
e <b>M/M/c</b>, <b>M/D/1</b>, or <b>M/G/1</b> depending on how the system b=
ehaves.</p> <p>And remember, you=E2=80=99re not doing this to impress anyon=
e with math. You=E2=80=99re doing it to make life easier for your team and =
your customers.<b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</b></p> <h2 id=3D"b-types-of-queuing-m=
odels-based-on-structure-b" class=3D"scroll-anchor"><b>Types of Queuing Mod=
els Based on Structure</b></h2> <p>Not all lines are created equal. Dependi=
ng on how your service flow is set up, the structure of your queuing models=
 can vary quite a bit. Understanding these structures is key to designing a=
 smoother experience=E2=80=94whether you're managing a helpdesk or a car wa=
sh.</p> <h3 id=3D"b-1-single-channel-single-phase-b" class=3D"scroll-anchor=
"><b>1. Single Channel, Single Phase</b></h3> <p>This is the simplest kind =
of queue you=E2=80=99ll find. One line, one server, one step.</p> <p>Imagin=
e there's a drive-through car wash: vehicles queue up in one lane, are wash=
ed individually, and drive off when finished. No stopping in between. No ha=
ndoffs. This is simple, clean, and efficient=E2=80=94provided the demand is=
n't greater than the rate of service.</p> <p>This kind of model is simple t=
o administer but can easily become a chokepoint if the service time is sign=
ificant or customer volumes surge. That's why it works best when work is sh=
ort and routine.</p> <p>In the queuing theory context, this model is typica=
lly expressed as <b>M/M/1</b>=E2=80=94a random arrival and service single-s=
erver model. It's one of the most frequently examined configurations and th=
e foundation for learning more advanced queuing processes later on.</p> <h3=
 id=3D"b-2-single-channel-multi-phase-b" class=3D"scroll-anchor"><b>2. Sing=
le Channel, Multi Phase</b></h3> <p>Now imagine walking into a bank to open=
 a new account. You first talk to a receptionist, then move to a clerk to f=
ill out paperwork, and finally speak with a manager for account approval. Y=
ou're still in one queue, but the service happens in multiple steps=E2=80=
=94this is what queuing theory calls a single channel, multi phase model.</=
p> <p>In this structure, there's one line feeding into a sequence of servic=
e stages, each handled by a different point along the way. It's common in p=
laces where tasks are more complex and can=E2=80=99t be wrapped up in one g=
o.</p> <p>From the perspective of the queuing process, this model helps bal=
ance the workload=E2=80=94each phase handles a specific part of the service=
. But it also means one slow step can cause the entire system to back up.</=
p> <p>This type of queue setup is a great real-world example of the applica=
tions of queuing theory in designing services that involve both volume and =
detail=E2=80=94like <a href=3D"https://www.qminder.com/industries/banking/"=
 rel=3D"external nofollow noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank">banks</a>,=
 clinics, or even immigration counters at airports.</p> <cta-with-image tit=
le=3D"Turn Long Waits Into Shorter Visits" demo-text=3D"See how Qminder hel=
ps hospitals reduce patient wait times with real-time queue updates, and se=
